WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:08.000
And we are moving to the next question, a very important question of our lecture, the question of managing turnover.

00:08.000 --> 00:13.000
If we have been talking about what is turnover capital of an enterprise,

00:13.000 --> 00:18.000
that is, we have defined it, indicating its importance for an enterprise,

00:18.000 --> 00:23.000
now comes the moment of how to manage this capital, how to manage it correctly,

00:23.000 --> 00:27.000
not to let it go to the dumps, so that the enterprise feels very good.

00:27.000 --> 00:32.000
This is the second, but the most important question of our lecture.

00:32.000 --> 00:43.000
The practice says that it is possible to choose three types of various policies of managing turnover capital.

00:43.000 --> 00:53.000
Aggressive, conservative and moderate centrist policy.

00:53.000 --> 00:56.000
Aggressive policy.

00:56.000 --> 01:03.000
An enterprise that has an aggressive policy of managing its capital is called a fat cat.

01:03.000 --> 01:07.000
Why? What is aggressive policy?

01:07.000 --> 01:12.000
Aggressive policy implies no restrictions on the growth of current assets.

01:12.000 --> 01:19.000
No restrictions. Current assets grow, increase, the enterprise feels amazing.

01:19.000 --> 01:24.000
All its resources are huge, it is aimed at increasing its assets.

01:24.000 --> 01:28.000
The reserves of this enterprise are gigantic.

01:28.000 --> 01:32.000
It never has a failure, it has no problems with deliveries.

01:32.000 --> 01:37.000
It has no failures, it has all the reserves, any reserves.

01:37.000 --> 01:40.000
Fat cat.

01:40.000 --> 01:42.000
The other side of the coin.

01:42.000 --> 01:47.000
Some of the reserves are dead reserves, unnecessary reserves.

01:47.000 --> 01:56.000
Taking all the risks into account, the enterprise freezes a huge amount of its assets in reserves.

01:56.000 --> 02:04.000
Naturally, the economic profitability of these assets is lower.

02:04.000 --> 02:07.000
But the enterprise has no problems.

02:07.000 --> 02:09.000
As they say, if it doesn't hurt, the head will go.

02:09.000 --> 02:20.000
No problems with failures in the production, supply and implementation process.

02:20.000 --> 02:26.000
Aggressive policy of managing capital is typical of passive policy.

02:26.000 --> 02:34.000
A sign of this policy is a significant pre-emphasis on short-term loan.

02:34.000 --> 02:43.000
The enterprise takes only short-term loans, uses them actively and returns them quickly.

02:43.000 --> 02:52.000
If short-term loans prevail among all passives, it means that the enterprise is aggressive.

02:52.000 --> 02:56.000
What does it give to the enterprise? Why does the enterprise use aggressive policy?

02:56.000 --> 03:01.000
A short-term loan has its pros and cons.

03:01.000 --> 03:05.000
The pro of a short-term loan is a lower interest rate.

03:05.000 --> 03:15.000
A short-term loan in a bank can be charged at a lower rate than a long-term loan.

03:15.000 --> 03:22.000
The second pro of short-term loans is that there are forms of loans

03:22.000 --> 03:33.000
that can be obtained for a period of a month without a deposit.

03:33.000 --> 03:37.000
But this form of loans has its cons.

03:37.000 --> 03:41.000
A short-term loan must be returned very quickly.

03:41.000 --> 03:49.000
Therefore, only a short-term loan can be used by an enterprise

03:49.000 --> 03:56.000
that quickly returns its profits to the enterprise.

03:56.000 --> 04:00.000
Only for such enterprises with a short cycle,

04:00.000 --> 04:06.000
such a policy of managing capital is possible and real.

04:06.000 --> 04:12.000
If an enterprise has a longer production cycle, it cannot use this policy.

04:13.000 --> 04:18.000
If an enterprise takes a short-term loan and invests it in the production process,

04:18.000 --> 04:22.000
it has no means to return it.

04:22.000 --> 04:26.000
At the same time, the use of such a policy gives the enterprise

04:26.000 --> 04:30.000
an additional higher level of financial leverage.

04:30.000 --> 04:34.000
Note that if the enterprise has a low interest rate,

04:34.000 --> 04:37.000
the profitability is high.

04:37.000 --> 04:40.000
If the enterprise has a high interest rate and profitability,

04:40.000 --> 04:43.000
the enterprise has a higher level of financial leverage

04:43.000 --> 04:48.000
and can earn a higher margin.

04:48.000 --> 04:53.000
Such a policy is chosen by large enterprises,

04:53.000 --> 04:57.000
which have a lot of money.

04:57.000 --> 05:01.000
And most importantly, such a policy is chosen by enterprises

05:01.000 --> 05:04.000
that cannot be allowed to fail.

05:04.000 --> 05:09.000
They cannot lose their partners, they cannot stop production.

05:09.000 --> 05:14.000
But imagine a metallurgical plant.

05:14.000 --> 05:18.000
What does it mean to have a shortage of supplies

05:18.000 --> 05:23.000
and, as a result, to stop the Martenovskaya domino oven?

05:23.000 --> 05:27.000
If you stop the domino oven,

05:27.000 --> 05:32.000
a goat is formed there, which must be removed from there with great difficulty.

05:32.000 --> 05:36.000
This is a loss of time, money, and so on.

05:36.000 --> 05:41.000
There is a production that cannot be stopped in any case.

05:41.000 --> 05:46.000
There must be a surplus of supplies,

05:46.000 --> 05:51.000
it must be insured in all cases.

05:51.000 --> 05:56.000
Here is the policy of a fat cat.

05:56.000 --> 06:01.000
There is a diametrically opposite policy of asset management.

06:01.000 --> 06:06.000
It is a conservative policy.

06:06.000 --> 06:09.000
It is a conservative policy,

06:09.000 --> 06:12.000
because it is used only by enterprises

06:12.000 --> 06:15.000
that have very little turnover.

06:15.000 --> 06:20.000
So little that they tremble for every penny.

06:20.000 --> 06:25.000
And they are forced to spend their money

06:25.000 --> 06:30.000
only on the most necessary assets.

06:30.000 --> 06:33.000
They calculate up to every penny,

06:33.000 --> 06:36.000
they spend it very rationally.

06:36.000 --> 06:39.000
Yes, because of this, their profitability is very high.

06:39.000 --> 06:43.000
They have a very rational use of money.

06:43.000 --> 06:48.000
But the opposite side, because they have very few assets,

06:48.000 --> 06:54.000
they can have a shortage.

06:54.000 --> 06:58.000
Therefore, a conservative policy can be used

06:58.000 --> 07:01.000
when you are forced from poverty,

07:01.000 --> 07:04.000
when you simply do not have enough money,

07:04.000 --> 07:07.000
and when every penny is on the account,

07:07.000 --> 07:10.000
or when the business is highly determined.

07:10.000 --> 07:13.000
If you have clearly scheduled needs in supplies

07:13.000 --> 07:16.000
and in the implementation of production,

07:16.000 --> 07:20.000
and your uncertainty is reduced to zero or its minimum value,

07:20.000 --> 07:24.000
then the amount of supplies can be reduced to the minimum value.

07:24.000 --> 07:27.000
You know exactly when and how much you need,

07:27.000 --> 07:30.000
and this is determined by the course of the production process.

07:30.000 --> 07:34.000
Therefore, in these two cases, a conservative policy is used.

07:34.000 --> 07:39.000
A sign of a conservative policy is a low interest rate

07:39.000 --> 07:44.000
of a short-term loan in the total amount of passives.

07:44.000 --> 07:47.000
That is, you pay very little to the bank,

07:47.000 --> 07:49.000
you take a loan.

07:49.000 --> 07:52.000
While the sign of a fat cat policy,

07:52.000 --> 07:54.000
an aggressive policy,

07:54.000 --> 07:58.000
is a high interest rate of short-term loans.

08:01.000 --> 08:04.000
In a conservative policy,

08:04.000 --> 08:08.000
all assets are financed by permanent passives,

08:08.000 --> 08:12.000
their own funds, long-term loans and loans.

08:12.000 --> 08:17.000
Because short-term loans are used very little.

08:18.000 --> 08:23.000
And, accordingly, the effect of the financial lever is quite low.

08:23.000 --> 08:26.000
And the third group of businessmen,

08:26.000 --> 08:29.000
enterprises that use politics,

08:29.000 --> 08:32.000
is moderate politics or centrists.

08:32.000 --> 08:37.000
They do not belong to fat cats or do not work poorly.

08:37.000 --> 08:40.000
They do not have excess assets

08:40.000 --> 08:43.000
or are not in a state

08:43.000 --> 08:47.000
when there are no excess assets.

08:47.000 --> 08:50.000
They are in the middle.

08:50.000 --> 08:53.000
This is an optimal value

08:53.000 --> 08:58.000
that avoids shortcomings that are inherent in the extreme.

08:58.000 --> 09:00.000
But at the same time,

09:00.000 --> 09:04.000
it does not give the advantages that these extremes have.

09:04.000 --> 09:07.000
Those who pursue a centrist policy,

09:07.000 --> 09:12.000
their risk of unpaid ability is at a certain average value.

09:12.000 --> 09:15.000
It is acceptable and convenient.

09:15.000 --> 09:18.000
No one makes any claims to them.

09:18.000 --> 09:20.000
But at the same time,

09:20.000 --> 09:23.000
they do not have excess money,

09:23.000 --> 09:28.000
thanks to which these risks can be reduced to zero.

09:28.000 --> 09:32.000
A sign of moderate politics of centrists

09:32.000 --> 09:37.000
is the absence or very low interest rate of short-term loans

09:37.000 --> 09:40.000
in the total amount of passives.

09:40.000 --> 09:45.000
There are practically no short-term loans.

09:45.000 --> 09:51.000
If we combine all the signs we listed in one table,

09:51.000 --> 09:55.000
we will get a matrix of the choice of politics,

09:55.000 --> 09:59.000
operative management of current assets and passives.

09:59.000 --> 10:03.000
Please look at the slide that is in front of you.

10:03.000 --> 10:05.000
You see the matrix

10:05.000 --> 10:09.000
in which the policy of management of current assets

10:09.000 --> 10:12.000
is divided into three types.

10:12.000 --> 10:15.000
We have just discussed three types.

10:15.000 --> 10:19.000
Aggressive, moderate and conservative.

10:19.000 --> 10:23.000
The intersection of these types of management

10:23.000 --> 10:26.000
gives us the financial policy

10:26.000 --> 10:29.000
that is applied at the enterprise.

10:29.000 --> 10:32.000
You can see from this slide

10:32.000 --> 10:37.000
that aggressive policy in relation to passives

10:38.000 --> 10:42.000
is not combined with conservative policy in relation to assets.

10:42.000 --> 10:44.000
It is impossible,

10:44.000 --> 10:46.000
there is no such enterprise

10:46.000 --> 10:49.000
that could use these two policies.

10:49.000 --> 10:52.000
The aggressive policy of assets,

10:52.000 --> 10:54.000
of fat cats,

10:54.000 --> 10:58.000
is not combined with conservative policy of passives.

10:58.000 --> 11:01.000
All other combinations are possible.

11:01.000 --> 11:04.000
The combination of two aggressive policies

11:04.000 --> 11:08.000
gives us an aggressive state of the enterprise.

11:08.000 --> 11:11.000
The enterprise uses only short-term loans

11:11.000 --> 11:14.000
and with the help of these loans

11:14.000 --> 11:18.000
it buys huge amounts of stock.

11:18.000 --> 11:21.000
It has no problems.

11:21.000 --> 11:24.000
It is an aggressive policy.

11:24.000 --> 11:28.000
The opposite is the case with the conservative policy

11:28.000 --> 11:31.000
of assets and passives.

11:31.000 --> 11:34.000
The enterprise takes care of every penny

11:34.000 --> 11:38.000
and looks at its expenses very scrupulously.

11:38.000 --> 11:40.000
At the same time,

11:40.000 --> 11:43.000
it does not use short-term loans,

11:43.000 --> 11:47.000
but only works with long-term loans.

11:47.000 --> 11:50.000
This is called the conservative policy

11:50.000 --> 11:53.000
of using assets and passives.

11:53.000 --> 11:56.000
All other combinations

11:56.000 --> 12:00.000
give us a moderate policy.

12:01.000 --> 12:07.000
A moderate policy of assets and passives.

12:09.000 --> 12:13.000
If you ask me what is the best form of policy

12:13.000 --> 12:16.000
for the enterprise,

12:16.000 --> 12:19.000
I will tell you that there is no such form

12:19.000 --> 12:21.000
that would be ideal,

12:21.000 --> 12:24.000
that you should strive for.

12:24.000 --> 12:27.000
The form is determined by the state

12:27.000 --> 12:30.000
of the enterprise.

12:30.000 --> 12:34.000
If the enterprise has a huge amount of money,

12:34.000 --> 12:38.000
it is more convenient for it to have an aggressive policy.

12:38.000 --> 12:41.000
Of course, such an enterprise

12:41.000 --> 12:44.000
is able to take care of its reputation

12:44.000 --> 12:47.000
in the market.

12:47.000 --> 12:50.000
It cannot afford any failures.

12:50.000 --> 12:54.000
Therefore, it leads an aggressive policy.

12:54.000 --> 12:58.000
The enterprise is not able to pay

12:58.000 --> 13:02.000
for its reliability in the market.

13:02.000 --> 13:05.000
On the contrary,

13:05.000 --> 13:08.000
when the enterprise has no money,

13:08.000 --> 13:12.000
it has no other policy but the conservative one.

13:12.000 --> 13:15.000
Life itself makes it work

13:15.000 --> 13:19.000
in the conditions of the conservative policy.

13:19.000 --> 13:23.000
If the enterprise is in a normal state,

13:23.000 --> 13:27.000
it leads a moderate policy.

13:27.000 --> 13:31.000
It uses short-term money,

13:31.000 --> 13:35.000
but it does not spend it left and right.

13:35.000 --> 13:39.000
It rationally invests it in the reserves.

13:39.000 --> 13:43.000
There is no surplus in these reserves.

13:43.000 --> 13:47.000
This is how the vast majority of enterprises work.

13:47.000 --> 13:51.000
If you want to work as a vast majority of enterprises,

13:51.000 --> 13:55.000
which is a normal state for a business,

13:55.000 --> 13:59.000
you should choose a moderate policy of cooperative management

13:59.000 --> 14:03.000
with the current assets and passives.

14:03.000 --> 14:07.000
Later we will talk about how the management

14:07.000 --> 14:11.000
of the elements of the turnover assets happens.

14:11.000 --> 14:15.000
One of the most important elements of the turnover assets,

14:15.000 --> 14:19.000
as we have discussed today, is the reserves.

14:19.000 --> 14:23.000
The reserves are the assets that are intended

14:23.000 --> 14:27.000
for the enterprise to function normally

14:27.000 --> 14:31.000
within its business cycle.

14:31.000 --> 14:35.000
In order to ensure a normal,

14:35.000 --> 14:39.000
rhythmic state of the enterprise.

14:39.000 --> 14:43.000
As you remember, the enterprise's production cycle

14:43.000 --> 14:47.000
consists of three parts.

14:47.000 --> 14:51.000
The first part is the raw materials purchase.

14:51.000 --> 14:55.000
There are the production processes.

14:55.000 --> 14:59.000
There is the unfinished production.

14:59.000 --> 15:03.000
Some of the raw materials are in the form of unfinished production.

15:03.000 --> 15:07.000
There is the finished product in the warehouse,

15:07.000 --> 15:11.000
which is not yet implemented.

15:11.000 --> 15:15.000
Some of the raw materials are in this form.

15:15.000 --> 15:19.000
Each of these forms is needed by the enterprise.

15:19.000 --> 15:23.000
It should only choose the optimal combination

15:23.000 --> 15:27.000
and distribute its reserves between these forms.

15:27.000 --> 15:31.000
And depending on how it distributes these reserves,

15:31.000 --> 15:35.000
the financial stability of this enterprise depends.

15:35.000 --> 15:39.000
We have already discussed today that the reserves

15:39.000 --> 15:43.000
are influenced not only by the production structure,

15:43.000 --> 15:47.000
but also by the seasonality.

15:47.000 --> 15:51.000
The reserves are also influenced by the purpose of the production.

15:51.000 --> 15:55.000
It happens that the product needs to be produced

15:55.000 --> 15:59.000
at a strictly defined date,

15:59.000 --> 16:03.000
and accordingly, the reserves need to be prepared

16:03.000 --> 16:07.000
for this date.

16:07.000 --> 16:11.000
We have already said that the reserves should be

16:11.000 --> 16:15.000
distributed in a way that is not

16:15.000 --> 16:19.000
in the way of the production process.

16:19.000 --> 16:23.000
What will the enterprise get?

16:23.000 --> 16:27.000
What negative aspects will be characteristic for the enterprise?

16:27.000 --> 16:31.000
We should know what is negative and what is not.

16:31.000 --> 16:35.000
This should be the evidence of the inoptimal

16:35.000 --> 16:39.000
distribution of the reserves.

16:39.000 --> 16:43.000
What is the evidence?

16:43.000 --> 16:47.000
First of all, if the quantity of reserves increases,

16:47.000 --> 16:51.000
it should tell us about the increase in the production volume.

16:51.000 --> 16:55.000
The larger the production volume,

16:55.000 --> 16:59.000
the larger the quantity of reserves.

16:59.000 --> 17:03.000
To produce more products, you need to buy more raw materials,

17:03.000 --> 17:07.000
to have more products in incomplete production,

17:07.000 --> 17:11.000
so the quantity of reserves is always compared

17:11.000 --> 17:15.000
with the quantity of production volume.

17:15.000 --> 17:19.000
If the quantity of reserves is the same,

17:19.000 --> 17:23.000
the quantity of production volume does not play a negative role.

17:23.000 --> 17:27.000
If the volume of production increases by two times,

17:27.000 --> 17:31.000
the quantity of reserves could also increase by two times.

17:31.000 --> 17:35.000
This is a normal state of operation of the enterprise.

17:35.000 --> 17:39.000
But if the quantity of reserves increases by two times,

17:39.000 --> 17:43.000
and the volume of production increases by 10%,

17:43.000 --> 17:47.000
this is not a normal state.

17:47.000 --> 17:51.000
We need to look closely at why this happened.

17:51.000 --> 17:55.000
Of course, if there was a lack of reserves before,

17:55.000 --> 17:59.000
this can indicate the transition to the optimal mode.

17:59.000 --> 18:03.000
But if before that we had an optimal reserve mode,

18:03.000 --> 18:07.000
then the increase of reserves is faster than the increase of production volume,

18:07.000 --> 18:11.000
which indicates that there is an abnormal increase in the reserves,

18:11.000 --> 18:15.000
and, accordingly, their freezing.

18:15.000 --> 18:19.000
The increase in the quantity of reserves is also used by the business

18:19.000 --> 18:23.000
to protect against inflation.

18:23.000 --> 18:27.000
If inflation grows at a very high rate,

18:27.000 --> 18:31.000
the business is protected from it.

18:31.000 --> 18:35.000
We, as individuals,

18:35.000 --> 18:39.000
at high rates of inflation were protected

18:39.000 --> 18:43.000
by the fact that we were transferring money from a weak currency

18:43.000 --> 18:47.000
to a stronger currency, for example, dollars or euros,

18:47.000 --> 18:51.000
and those that had less inflation

18:51.000 --> 18:55.000
were able to save their money.

18:55.000 --> 18:59.000
Legal entities do not have the opportunity

18:59.000 --> 19:03.000
to transfer money from one currency to another,

19:03.000 --> 19:07.000
so they use another form of saving money in the condition of inflation.

19:07.000 --> 19:11.000
They increase their reserves.

19:11.000 --> 19:15.000
The thing is that the reserves that have been acquired

19:15.000 --> 19:19.000
have not grown in price.

19:19.000 --> 19:23.000
They have been bought, and they are available,

19:23.000 --> 19:27.000
and can be used at any time.

19:27.000 --> 19:31.000
But after some time,

19:31.000 --> 19:35.000
those same reserves will cost more.

19:35.000 --> 19:39.000
Therefore, in the condition of inflation,

19:39.000 --> 19:43.000
free money was used to buy reserves.

19:43.000 --> 19:47.000
They are still needed, they will still be used in production.

19:47.000 --> 19:51.000
It is more profitable to store them in reserves than to depreciate them.

19:51.000 --> 19:55.000
Another thing is that here, again,

19:55.000 --> 19:59.000
you can store money in the form of reserves,

19:59.000 --> 20:03.000
you can store it in another form, for example, in a bank deposit.

20:03.000 --> 20:07.000
You can only compare what is economically more profitable

20:07.000 --> 20:11.000
to invest in a bank at a percentage,

20:11.000 --> 20:15.000
or to protect from inflation.

20:15.000 --> 20:19.000
The mechanism that will give more benefit is more profitable to use.

20:19.000 --> 20:23.000
Usually,

20:23.000 --> 20:27.000
it is more profitable to protect from inflation

20:27.000 --> 20:31.000
than to use it as a deposit.

20:31.000 --> 20:35.000
Therefore, enterprises increase the volume of reserves,

20:35.000 --> 20:39.000
preferring to increase the investment of money in deposits.

20:45.000 --> 20:49.000
The ineffectiveness of the use of reserves

20:49.000 --> 20:53.000
is also caused by excessive freezing of reserves

20:53.000 --> 20:57.000
in the form of unfulfilled production

20:57.000 --> 21:01.000
or in the form of reserves in the raw material warehouse.

21:01.000 --> 21:05.000
If there is an excessive amount of reserves,

21:05.000 --> 21:09.000
it leads to the fact that enterprises

21:09.000 --> 21:13.000
are not effectively using their money.

21:13.000 --> 21:17.000
Therefore, excessive increase of reserves is harmful.

21:17.000 --> 21:21.000
When we have a shortage of reserves at the enterprise,

21:21.000 --> 21:25.000
it is also not good.

21:25.000 --> 21:29.000
If the enterprise is short of reserves,

21:29.000 --> 21:33.000
then the enterprise starts to break down in production,

21:33.000 --> 21:37.000
the rhythm of production is disrupted.

21:37.000 --> 21:41.000
This is also bad, because the enterprise is in a frenzy,

21:41.000 --> 21:45.000
it stops.

21:45.000 --> 21:49.000
There are no steering wheels,

21:49.000 --> 21:53.000
and the whole auto-vase has stopped.

21:53.000 --> 21:57.000
The small detail, from which the entire conveyor of the auto-vase has stopped.

21:57.000 --> 22:01.000
Everything is needed.

22:01.000 --> 22:05.000
The enterprise should work rhythmically, without interruptions.

22:05.000 --> 22:09.000
Therefore, there should be a sufficient amount of reserves.

22:09.000 --> 22:13.000
Another thing is that the shortage of reserves

22:13.000 --> 22:17.000
is overloaded.

22:17.000 --> 22:21.000
And it starts to produce less than it is able to produce.

22:21.000 --> 22:25.000
The volume of the enterprise's income

22:25.000 --> 22:29.000
decreases.

22:29.000 --> 22:33.000
The enterprise receives less income than it can produce.

22:33.000 --> 22:37.000
If the enterprise does not work

22:37.000 --> 22:41.000
with its maximum capacity,

22:41.000 --> 22:45.000
its production cost increases.

22:45.000 --> 22:49.000
The fact is that the enterprise has all the main means

22:49.000 --> 22:53.000
that are amortized.

22:53.000 --> 22:57.000
If the enterprise reduces the volume of production,

22:57.000 --> 23:01.000
then more and more funds are needed

23:01.000 --> 23:05.000
to amortize the production.

23:05.000 --> 23:09.000
Remember, we once said that it is much more profitable

23:09.000 --> 23:13.000
to produce more pencils than one pencil.

23:13.000 --> 23:17.000
Because one pencil amortizes the entire enterprise.

23:17.000 --> 23:21.000
And the cost of a pencil is so huge

23:21.000 --> 23:25.000
that it is like gold.

